s="css-xejapu e12qa4dv0"><div id="sponsor-wrapper" class="css-1hyfx7x"><div id="sponsor-slug" class="css-19vbshk"><p>Supported by</p></div><a href="#after-sponsor" class="css-777zgl">SKIP ADVERTISEMENT</a><div class="ad sponsor-wrapper css-rfqw0c" id="sponsor"></div><div id="after-sponsor"></div></div><p class="css-9ogeoa e6idgb70">Theater Review</p><div class="css-1vkm6nb ehdk2mb0"><h1 id="link-4a88254c" class="css-qmhsi0 e1h9rw200" data-testid="headline">Filling the Silence With the Voice of Youth</h1></div><div role="toolbar" data-testid="share-tools" aria-label="Social Media Share buttons, Save button, and Comments Panel with current comment count" class="css-mfml7"><div class="css-1q9ot06"><ul class="css-1liwv7v"><li class="css-1gh9hw8"><div class="css-vxcmzt"><div class="css-79elbk"><button type="button" aria-label="" aria-expanded="false" class="css-1eeh360 actionbar-button" data-testid="gift-article-button"><span class="css-lu72is"><svg aria-hidden="true" width="19" height="19" viewBox="0 0 19 19" class="sha-gift-icon"><path d="M18.04 5.293h-2.725c.286-.34.493-.74.606-1.17a2.875 2.875 0 0 0-.333-2.322A2.906 2.906 0 0 0 13.64.48a3.31 3.31 0 0 0-2.372.464 3.775 3.775 0 0 0-1.534 2.483l-.141.797-.142-.847A3.745 3.745 0 0 0 7.927.923 3.31 3.31 0 0 0 5.555.459 2.907 2.907 0 0 0 3.607 1.78a2.877 2.877 0 0 0-.333 2.321c.117.429.324.828.606 1.171H1.155a.767.767 0 0 0-.757.757v3.674a.767.767 0 0 0 .757.757h.424v7.53A1.01 1.01 0 0 0 2.588 19h14.13a1.01 1.01 0 0 0 1.01-.959v-7.56h.424a.758.758 0 0 0 .757-.757V6.05a.759.759 0 0 0-.868-.757Zm-7.196-1.625a2.665 2.665 0 0 1 1.01-1.736 2.24 2.24 0 0 1 1.574-.313 1.817 1.817 0 0 1 1.211.818 1.857 1.857 0 0 1 .202 1.453 2.2 2.2 0 0 1-.838 1.191h-3.431l.272-1.413ZM4.576 2.386a1.837 1.837 0 0 1 1.221-.817 2.23 2.23 0 0 1 1.565.313 2.624 2.624 0 0 1 1.01 1.736l.242 1.453H5.182a2.2 2.2 0 0 1-.838-1.19 1.857 1.857 0 0 1 .202-1.495h.03ZM1.548 6.424h7.54V9.39h-7.58l.04-2.967Zm1.181 4.128h6.359v7.287H2.729v-7.287Zm13.777 7.287h-6.348v-7.307h6.348v7.307Zm1.181-8.468h-7.53V6.404h7.53V9.37Z" fill="#121212" fill-rule="nonzero"></path></svg><svg aria-hidden="true" width="23" height="18" viewBox="0 0 23 18" class="sha-arrow-icon"><path d="M1.357 17.192a.663.663 0 0 1-.642-.81c1.82-7.955 6.197-12.068 12.331-11.68V1.127a.779.779 0 0 1 .42-.653.726.726 0 0 1 .78.106l8.195 6.986a.81.81 0 0 1 .253.557.82.82 0 0 1-.263.547l-8.196 6.955a.83.83 0 0 1-.779.105.747.747 0 0 1-.42-.663V11.29c-8.418-.905-10.974 5.177-11.08 5.45a.662.662 0 0 1-.6.453Zm10.048-7.26a16.37 16.37 0 0 1 2.314.158.81.81 0 0 1 .642.726v3.02l6.702-5.682-6.702-5.692v2.883a.767.767 0 0 1-.242.536.747.747 0 0 1-.547.18c-4.808-.537-8.364 1.85-10.448 6.922a11.679 11.679 0 0 1 8.28-3.093v.042Z" fill="#000" fill-rule="nonzero"></path></svg>Share full article</span></button></div></div></li><li class="css-2ykviq sha-std-share"><div class="css-vxcmzt"><div class="css-79elbk"><button type="button" aria-label="More sharing options ..." aria-expanded="false" class="css-1nurhyi actionbar-button"><svg aria-hidden="true" width="23" height="18" viewBox="0 0 23 18" class="css-zd9juy"><path d="M1.357 17.192a.663.663 0 0 1-.642-.81c1.82-7.955 6.197-12.068 12.331-11.68V1.127a.779.779 0 0 1 .42-.653.726.726 0 0 1 .78.106l8.195 6.986a.81.81 0 0 1 .253.557.82.82 0 0 1-.263.547l-8.196 6.955a.83.83 0 0 1-.779.105.747.747 0 0 1-.42-.663V11.29c-8.418-.905-10.974 5.177-11.08 5.45a.662.662 0 0 1-.6.453Zm10.048-7.26a16.37 16.37 0 0 1 2.314.158.81.81 0 0 1 .642.726v3.02l6.702-5.682-6.702-5.692v2.883a.767.767 0 0 1-.242.536.747.747 0 0 1-.547.18c-4.808-.537-8.364 1.85-10.448 6.922a11.679 11.679 0 0 1 8.28-3.093v.042Z" fill="#000" fill-rule="nonzero"></path></svg></button></div></div></li><li class="css-2ykviq save-button"><button type="button" role="switch" class="css-1yhvmgx actionbar-button" data-testid="save-article-button" aria-label="Save article for reading later..." aria-checked="false" disabled="" aria-busy="false" aria-live="polite"><svg width="12" height="18" viewBox="0 0 12 18" class="css-eap6fy"><g fill-rule="nonzero"><path class="saved-fill" d="M1.157 1.268v14.288l4.96-3.813 4.753 3.843V1.268z"></path><path class="saved-stroke" d="m12 18-5.9-4.756L0 17.98V1.014C0 .745.095.487.265.297.435.107.664 0 .904 0h10.192c.24 0 .47.107.64.297.169.19.264.448.264.717V18ZM1.157 1.268v14.288l4.96-3.813 4.753 3.843V1.268H1.158Z"></path></g></svg></button></li></ul></div></div><div data-testid="imageblock-wrapper"><figure class="sizeMedium layoutHorizontal css-10j5xkt" aria-label="media" role="group"><div class="css-1xb94ky" data-testid="imageContainer-children-Image"><img alt="" class="css-rq4mmj" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2012/06/19/arts/SLOW/SLOW-articleLarge.jpg?quality=75&amp;auto=webp&amp;disable=upscale" srcSet="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2012/06/19/arts/SLOW/SLOW-articleLarge.jpg?quality=75&amp;auto=webp 600w,https://static01.nyt.com/images/2012/06/19/arts/SLOW/SLOW-jumbo.jpg?quality=75&amp;auto=webp 1024w,https://static01.nyt.com/images/2012/06/19/arts/SLOW/SLOW-superJumbo.jpg?quality=75&amp;auto=webp 2048w" sizes="((min-width: 600px) and (max-width: 1004px)) 84vw, (min-width: 1005px) 60vw, 100vw" decoding="async" width="600" height="344"/></div><figcaption data-testid="photoviewer-children-ImageCaption" class="css-1ifeaca e3rygrp0"><span class="css-jevhma e13ogyst0"><strong class="css-8qgvsz ebyp5n10">Slowgirl</strong>, by Greg Pierce, with Sarah Steele and Zeljko Ivanek, is playing at the new Claire Tow Theater at Lincoln Center.</span><span class="css-1u46b97 e1z0qqy90"><span class="css-1ly73wi e1tej78p0">Credit...</span><span><span aria-hidden="false">Karli Cadel for The New York Times</span></span></span></figcaption></figure></div><div class="css-3xipl4"><div class="css-1undj8r"><div class="css-83hgbf"><dl itemscope=""><dt>Slowgirl</dt></dl></div></div></div><div data-testid="byline-timestamp" class="css-xt80pu eakwutd0"><div class="css-103l8m3"><div class="css-1e2jphy epjyd6m1"><div class="css-233int epjyd6m0"><p class="css-4anu6l e1jsehar1"><span class="byline-prefix">By </span><span class="css-1baulvz last-byline" itemProp="name"><a href="https://www.nytimes.com/by/charles-isherwood" class="css-n8ff4n e1jsehar0">Charles Isherwood</a></span></p></div></div><div data-testid="reading-time-module" class="css-8atqhb"><ul class="css-1cgskve epjyd6m3"><li class="css-ccw2r3 epjyd6m2"><time class="css-1z1nqv e16638kd0" dateTime="2012-06-18T22:00:20-04:00">June 18, 2012</time></li></ul></div></div></div></header><section name="articleBody" class="meteredContent css-1r7ky0e"><div class="css-s99gbd StoryBodyCompanionColumn"><div class="css-53u6y8"><p class="css-at9mc1 evys1bk0">The scrabbling of iguanas across a metal roof, the squawk of a parrot and other colorful noises are resounding throughout the Claire Tow Theater, the <a class="css-yywogo" href="http://www.nytimes.com/2012/05/15/theater/lincoln-center-theater-to-open-claire-tow-theater-for-lct3.html?_r=1" title="New York Times article on new theater">handsome new auditorium</a> built atop Lincoln Center Theater’s Broadway home, the Vivian Beaumont Theater. But the truly exotic note in the jungle symphony of Greg Pierce’s play “Slowgirl” is the adrenaline chatter of the 17-year-old American girl who finds herself in the alien environment of rural Costa Rica. Her anxious, endless nattering reverberates like a constant klaxon horn amid the silence inhabited by her uncle, who has retreated from the world to live in solitude with nature. </p><p class="css-at9mc1 evys1bk0">Mr. Pierce’s play, which inaugurates the company’s new permanent home for its <a class="css-yywogo" href="http://lct.org/aboutLct3.htm" title="LCT3 Web site" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank">LCT3</a> program, is a modest, sensitively drawn <a class="css-yywogo" href="http://www.nytimes.com/2010/05/09/theater/09two.html?pagewanted=allq" title="Charles Isherwood essay on two-handers">two-hander</a> about the emotional common ground established between Becky (Sarah Steele) and her Uncle Sterling (Zeljko Ivanek) during her visit to his remote home in the countryside. A traumatic accident Becky was involved in has led to her suspension from high school. The drama bears a notable structural and thematic similarity to <a class="css-yywogo" href="http://theater.nytimes.com/2012/04/03/theater/reviews/4000-miles-at-the-mitzi-e-newhouse-theater.html" title="New York Times review">“4000 Miles,”</a> the superb play by Amy Herzog that’s being performed a few floors down at Lincoln Center Theater’s other stage, the Mitzi Newhouse, through July 1. Both depict the tentative but warming relationship between members of two generations of a family, the younger of whom is struggling with guilt and disorientation after a recent trauma.</p><p class="css-at9mc1 evys1bk0">Mr. Pierce’s appealing, low-key play may be less substantial and emotionally rewarding than Ms. Herzog’s, but he displays a similar gift for capturing the herky-jerky rhythms of contemporary speech, and an appreciation of how deliberate pacing can invite an audience more deeply into the theatrical experience. </p></div><aside class="css-ew4tgv" aria-label="companion column"></aside></div><div><div data-testid="imageblock-wrapper"><figure class="img-sz-medium css-mqw7kw e1g7ppur0" aria-label="media" role="group"><div class="css-1xdhyk6 erfvjey0" data-testid="photoviewer-children-figure"><span class="css-1ly73wi e1tej78p0">Image</span><div class="css-nwd8t8" data-testid="lazy-image"><div data-testid="lazyimage-container" style="height:257.9036458333333px"></div></div></div><figcaption data-testid="photoviewer-children-caption" class="css-gbc9ki ewdxa0s0"><span class="css-jevhma e13ogyst0">Zeljko Ivanek, as an uncle of few words, gets an earful from his niece, played by Sarah Steele.</span><span class="css-1u46b97 e1z0qqy90"><span class="css-1ly73wi e1tej78p0">Credit...</span><span><span aria-hidden="false">Karli Cadel for The New York Times</span></span></span></figcaption></figure></div></div><div class="css-s99gbd StoryBodyCompanionColumn"><div class="css-53u6y8"><p class="css-at9mc1 evys1bk0">As the play begins, Becky has just arrived after a long flight from the United States, rousing her uncle from napping over a book to shower him with the contents of her disorderly but curious mind. Mr. Pierce nails the voice of this character with a precision that had me smiling almost immediately: Anyone who has spent any time with a teenage American girl in recent years will recognize the dynamic cadences and machine-gun rhythms of her voice, the long arias of “I’m-like-whatever-she’s-like-oh-my-God-we-were-both-like-so-horrified” that can be aggravating and somehow delightful at the same time. </p></div><aside class="css-ew4tgv" aria-label="companion column"></aside></div><div></div><div class="css-s99gbd StoryBodyCompanionColumn"><div class="css-53u6y8"><p class="css-at9mc1 evys1bk0">Becky’s lack of inhibition — she casually asks after booze and pot — and her compulsive need to fill the air with the sound of her voice are in striking, comical contrast to the reticence of Sterling, who responds to her endless questions and conversational sallies with answers of an almost absurd minimalism. Sterling has been living in virtual isolation for so long that he has lost the art of casual conversation — and the need for it too. (In one of the play’s funniest lines, the exasperated Becky says, “Jesus, would it kill you to finish a sentence?”)</p><p class="css-at9mc1 evys1bk0">This constant chatter isn’t just time-filling, we soon learn. Although Becky is at first forthright about the reasons for her visit, as the play slowly unfolds, the deeper layers of unease, guilt and fear that underlie her obsessive need to talk are gradually revealed. </p><p class="css-at9mc1 evys1bk0">The tragic accident that led to Becky’s suspension took place at a party. The school misfit — Marybeth is her name, but because of a learning disability, her cruel nickname is “Slowgirl” — had been there, and after ingesting a few too many Jell-O shots, she became the object of a prank that was meant to be innocuous but turned calamitous. </p></div><aside class="css-ew4tgv" aria-label="companion column"></aside></div><div><figure class="sizeMedium css-sx232s" aria-label="media" role="group" data-testid="VideoBlock"><div class="css-1xb94ky"><span class="css-1dv1kvn">Video</span><div><div class="css-n27z15" style="padding-bottom:56.25%"><div class="css-mm3pwi"></div><div class="css-1cueeje" style="padding-bottom:56.25%;transition:opacity 300ms ease-in-out"><div class="css-1ihorw"><img src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2012/06/24/arts/video-slowgirl/video-slowgirl-articleLarge.jpg" alt="Video player loading"/></div><div class="css-ew1078"><div class="css-ptry2i"><div></div><div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div><figcaption class="css-1ifeaca e3rygrp0"><span class="css-jevhma e13ogyst0">Zeljko Ivanek and Sarah Steele in a scene from Greg Pierce&#x27;s play at the Claire Tow Theater.</span></figcaption></figure></div><div></div><div class="css-s99gbd StoryBodyCompanionColumn"><div class="css-53u6y8"><p class="css-at9mc1 evys1bk0">Becky has been accused of being involved, and may face serious charges if Marybeth, who was left in a coma, does not recover. Although it emerges only gradually, after a series of blunt questions from Becky, Sterling’s decision to withdraw from the world was inspired by a similar sense of perhaps unwarranted guilt.</p><p class="css-at9mc1 evys1bk0">Under the evenly paced direction of Anne Kauffman, Mr. Ivanek, a veteran stage actor nominated for a Tony for the 2006 revival of <a class="css-yywogo" href="http://theater.nytimes.com/2006/05/08/theater/reviews/08cain.html" title="New York Times review">“The Caine Mutiny Court-Martial,”</a> gives a performance of great skill and subtlety. Establishing through physical awkwardness just how ill at ease he feels in his skin, Mr. Ivanek’s Sterling seems to tread gingerly in his own home. Much of his discomfort probably derives from the unsettling presence of his brash niece, who appears so self-assured that she can make light of the tragedy she bore witness to. </p><p class="css-at9mc1 evys1bk0">Ms. Steele, a distinctive, up-and-coming actress who has made fine appearances Off Broadway in “Speech and Debate” and more recently <a class="css-yywogo" href="http://theater.nytimes.com/2012/01/31/theater/reviews/russian-transport-starring-janeane-garofalo.html?scp=1&amp;sq=russian%20transport&amp;st=cse" title="New York Times review">“Russian Transport,”</a> is wonderful as Becky, a young woman you would most definitely not want to be sitting next to on, say, a nine-hour flight to Central America. It takes a particular skill to make Mr. Pierce’s precisely calibrated language feel as natural — and, yes, at times as maddening — as it does in real life. But Ms. Steele more crucially possesses an ability to bring the wounds and uncertainty underlying Becky’s egoism quietly to the fore.</p><p class="css-at9mc1 evys1bk0">After a slightly predictable climactic scene of confession, “Slowgirl” winds down slowly to a whispering conclusion. Becky’s long rivulets of abrasive if funny chatter have subsided into a more studied conversational tone comfortably in rhythm with her uncle’s natural taciturnity. The shelter of words is no longer necessary to Becky — as it has long been unnecessary to Sterling — because he has helped her to find the courage to speak the plain truth. </p></div><aside class="css-ew4tgv" aria-label="companion column"></aside></div></section><div class="bottom-of-article"><div class="css-19vx93s"></div><div class="css-y1gt6f"></div><div class="css-13ldwoe">A version of this article appears in print on <span class="css-1dmwf73"> </span>, Section <!-- -->C<!-- -->, Page <!-- -->1<!-- --> of the New York edition<!-- --> with the headline: <!-- -->Filling the Silence With the Voice of Youth<span>. <a href="https://www.parsintl.com/publication/the-new-york-times/">Order Reprints</a> | <a href="https://www.nytimes.com/section/todayspaper">Today’s Paper</a> | <a href="https://www.nytimes.com/subscriptions/Multiproduct/lp8HYKU.html?campaignId=48JQY">Subscribe</a></span></div><div role="toolbar" data-testid="share-tools" aria-label="Social Media Share buttons, Save button, and Comments Panel with current comment count" class="css-mfml7"><div class="css-10i3hc"></div><div class="css-jf7ug7"><ul class="css-1liwv7v"><li class="css-1gh9hw8"><div class="css-vxcmzt"><div class="css-79elbk"><button type="button" aria-label="" aria-expanded="false" class="css-1eeh360 actionbar-button" data-testid="gift-article-button"><span class="css-lu72is"><svg aria-hidden="true" width="19" height="19" viewBox="0 0 19 19" class="sha-gift-icon"><path d="M18.04 5.293h-2.725c.286-.34.493-.74.606-1.17a2.875 2.875 0 0 0-.333-2.322A2.906 2.906 0 0 0 13.64.48a3.31 3.31 0 0 0-2.372.464 3.775 3.775 0 0 0-1.534 2.483l-.141.797-.142-.847A3.745 3.745 0 0 0 7.927.923 3.31 3.31 0 0 0 5.555.459 2.907 2.907 0 0 0 3.607 1.78a2.877 2.877 0 0 0-.333 2.321c.117.429.324.828.606 1.171H1.155a.767.767 0 0 0-.757.757v3.674a.767.767 0 0 0 .757.757h.424v7.53A1.01 1.01 0 0 0 2.588 19h14.13a1.01 1.01 0 0 0 1.01-.959v-7.56h.424a.758.758 0 0 0 .757-.757V6.05a.759.759 0 0 0-.868-.757Zm-7.196-1.625a2.665 2.665 0 0 1 1.01-1.736 2.24 2.24 0 0 1 1.574-.313 1.817 1.817 0 0 1 1.211.818 1.857 1.857 0 0 1 .202 1.453 2.2 2.2 0 0 1-.838 1.191h-3.431l.272-1.413ZM4.576 2.386a1.837 1.837 0 0 1 1.221-.817 2.23 2.23 0 0 1 1.565.313 2.624 2.624 0 0 1 1.01 1.736l.242 1.453H5.182a2.2 2.2 0 0 1-.838-1.19 1.857 1.857 0 0 1 .202-1.495h.03ZM1.548 6.424h7.54V9.39h-7.58l.04-2.967Zm1.181 4.128h6.359v7.287H2.729v-7.287Zm13.777 7.287h-6.348v-7.307h6.348v7.307Zm1.181-8.468h-7.53V6.404h7.53V9.37Z" fill="#121212" fill-rule="nonzero"></path></svg><svg aria-hidden="true" width="23" height="18" viewBox="0 0 23 18" class="sha-arrow-icon"><path d="M1.357 17.192a.663.663 0 0 